content.text: JavaScript Function call()
Method Reuse
With the call() method, you can write a method that can be used on different objects.
content.html: With the call() method, you can write a method that can be used on different objects.

content.text: All Functions are Methods
In JavaScript all functions are object methods.
content.html: In JavaScript all functions are object methods.

content.text: If a function is not a method of a JavaScript object, it is a function of the global object (see previous chapter).
content.html: If a function is not a method of a JavaScript object, it is a function of the global object (see previous chapter).

content.text: The example below creates an object with 3 properties, firstName, lastName, fullName.
content.html: The example below creates an object with 3 properties, firstName, lastName, fullName.

content.code_html:
const person = {
  firstName:"John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  fullName: function () {
    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
  }
}

// This will return "John Doe":
 person.fullName();

content.text: In the example above, this refers to the person object .
content.html: In the example above, this refers to the person object.

content.text: this.firstName means the firstName property of this .
Same as:
this.firstName means the firstName property of person .
What is this ?
In JavaScript, the this keyword refers to an object .
content.html: In JavaScript, the this keyword refers to an object.

content.text: The this keyword refers to different objects depending on how it is used:
content.html: The this keyword refers to different objects depending on how it is used:

content.text: Note
this is not a variable. It is a keyword. You cannot change the value of this .
content.html: this is not a variable. It is a keyword. You cannot change the value of this.

content.text: See Also:
The JavaScript this Tutorial
The JavaScript call() Method
The call() method is a predefined JavaScript method.
content.html: The call() method is a predefined JavaScript method.

content.text: It can be used to invoke (call) a method with an object as an argument (parameter).
content.html: It can be used to invoke (call) a method with an object as an argument (parameter).

content.text: Note
With call() , an object can use a method belonging to another object.
content.html: With call(), an object can use a method belonging to another object.

content.text: This example calls the fullName method of person, using it on person1 :
content.html: This example calls the fullName method of person, using it on person1:

content.code_html:
const person = {
  fullName: function() {
    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
  }
}
const person1 = {
  firstName:"John",
  lastName: "Doe"
}
const person2 = {
  firstName:"Mary",
  lastName: "Doe"
}

// This will return "John Doe":
 person.fullName.call(person1);

content.text: This example calls the fullName method of person, using it on person2 :
content.html: This example calls the fullName method of person, using it on person2:

content.code_html:
const person = {
  fullName: function() {
    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
  }
}
const person1 = {
  firstName:"John",
  lastName: "Doe"
}
const person2 = {
  firstName:"Mary",
  lastName: "Doe"
}

// This will return "Mary Doe"
 person.fullName.call(person2);

content.text: The call() Method with Arguments
The call() method can accept arguments:

content.code_html:
const person = {
  fullName: function(city, country) {
    return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName + "," + city + "," + country;
  }
}

const person1 = {
  firstName:"John",
  lastName: "Doe"
}

person.fullName.call(person1, "Oslo", "Norway");
